The ossuary house still fascinates after 100 years. Take a look inside Gaudi.
The roof is similar to the back of a prehistoric sauna, the staircase to a spine of dinosaurs and the balconies to open fish gills.
This is the house Casa Battlo in Barcelona by architect Antoni Gaudi.
Due to its organic forms, the house received the nickname of Maison in bone from the premises.
Organic shapes, wild colors, unusual use of stones, fragments of tiles and mosaics, facade recalling stairs and all over the curves, this is what is special for the New Art of Antoni Gaudi.
The front face of the house takes place its dream lines, its nice colors and textures that remind nature and animals.
During a more detailed observation, we can see geometry, rhythm and order thought precisely.
In the night the facade of the house becomes even more dramatic and is lit in such a way that the impression of the brightness of the colors is strengthened.
The rolling and twisting of shapes also appears in the interior with the same measure.
The wood in waves copies the window frames, the balustrades, the decorative elements of the doors, the eyelids and the blades.
The house Battlo, which stands in the Eixample district in the shopping street Passeig de Gracia to number 43, was born of the construction of a house of 1877 by the architect Emilio Sala Cortes.
The reconstruction took place for two years and the house completed in 1906.
The investor, Joseph Battlo, a rich entrepreneur, first insisted on demolishing the old construction and construction of another new one, but quickly accepted Gaudi's idea of an unusual and better market reconstruction.
But the idea of Casa Battlo as a multi-housed house was not thought by Gaudi alone.
The architect Joseph Maria Jujol worked with him.
It was precisely on his project that decorations were made for an apartment representing the owner of the building and the use of the mosaic for the facade.
Other artists and creators also worked for the facade.
The joint work for the Casa Battlo house plans began with a successful cooperation between Jujol and Gaudi.
Jujol participated in the construction of the house of Gaudi Casa Mila and of the Guell Park where there are other works of Gaudi.
The premises have named the hot house just after its completion due to its organic forms "the house in the bone".
Others, considering the specific window opening mechanism, called it "the house that dances".
It is said that above the construction there is a sword similar to that of Saint Georges the patron of the Catalogue.
Other elements of construction sculpture contain hidden religious motives.
Gaudi thought for the house a unique system in its central heating time, with air events and typical fireplaces.
Their 45 degree inclination seems strange.
During the creation of Gaudi did not comply with the construction directives at the time and was not allowed to interfere with them.
At the beginning of the construction, he obtained permission from the city to build, knowing, of course, that the data on the reconstruction plans were so vague that two years after the completion, the municipal council was horrified and asked for changes.
He was not pleased, for example, with the members of the municipal council that the construction pillars imposed on the public road.
There was never a change, but, on the contrary, only 15 days after the call of the city of Josep Battlo requested (and obtained satisfaction) the permission to rent the two highest floors.
The owner moved to the lower floors.
In the gallery on the second floor there was a common living room and a private room and part of the apartment.
The floor was rented to a jewelry store.
The whole six-storey house is shared by a staircase through which you can access up to an independent roof terrace.
All right angles and straight lines were cancelled by the basic elements of reconstruction and their replacement by curved walls.
Gaudi also works on the modern concept of connection of spaces.
The common part can be fully connected by opening the doors of the halls and the high society can communicate comfortably or be limited to private space for more intimate interviews.
The house with the reconstruction of Gaudi also received new facades a non-traditional roof and two additional floors.
Gaudi's game with light is also impressive, blue and white glass tiles with which the inner court is decorated and with light wells.
The two-colour game gives maximum light in all floors of the house.
It was simply enough to bet on the principle that white reflects more than the shadow that, on the contrary, absorbs the rays of the sun.
The Casa Battlo house that was registered in 2005 in the UNESCO World Heritage Fund may have been visited by everyone.
On the first floor of the house is the most spacious and most beautiful apartment accessible to the public.
The owners decided to take this step in 2002 on the occasion of the 150th anniversary of the birth of the famous creator.
They continued their visits because they found it to be a profitable business and extended the scope of the visits to common spaces and to the border, including roof terraces.
The ticket to the monument is not really expensive and costs 16.50 euros; students, retirees, groups and card holders have 20 percent discounts.
The sum is still above the entry price in Gaudi's other buildings in the city.
If you want to feel the real atmosphere of the house with its fantastic tours, you must quickly find a friend among the inhabitants of the building and visit the house completely.
