Devices to monitor people are increasingly being asked by parents who want to monitor their children.
The fear of their children has led more and more people to think about monitoring them through a GPS.
The system, set up at the beginning to search for cars, can also be used to track the movement of people and help in some cases, such as the one of the little Anicka Janatkova.
The instrument is now as large as a box of lamps but will soon be of the size of a watch.
The case of little Anicka has emanated a large number of people and they have begun to look for ways to better protect their children.
Even if the price is to disturb their private lives.
"We are trying to tell everyone that it is not espionage but only another way to reduce the likelihood that there is another tragedy," says Petr Pilin of Macro Weil, who is one of the suppliers of tracking devices on the Czech market.
"I realize that there may be cases of misuse of such devices, such as putting them in the bag of a person who is not aware of it, but I have not yet met such cases."
"Most people are customers who actually buy the product for security reasons," added Pilin.
According to him, children should always know for what purposes "the box" is used and how to use it in case of emergency.
Children's psychologist Dana Bockova draws attention to the fact that if the child does not want to wear such a thing, he will get rid of it.
'And even the smallest ones can show great creativity when it comes to getting rid of something explicitly when they don't want to be under control.'
"The mobile phones, which can cut themselves like these tracking devices, have already brought their parents to long expectations," Bockova says.
According to her, the fact that this type of device can help in the event of aggression is highly controversial.
"If this is a prepared kidnapping, the author will do everything to ensure that the child does not have an electronic device that can locate it."
"Currently, it's the phone."
"As soon as the tracking devices develop, they (criminals) will also search for them because the sale will be supported by an advertising campaign."
"In such cases, criminals will always be on the police," says the psychologist.
She agrees, however, that such devices can help when an attack is not prepared by a pedophile.
According to Robert Cech of RC Monitoring, which offers tracking services for both cars and people, says that having this type of device can help, even if it is destroyed in the event of an aggression.
"The apparatus may be so measured as to be in regular emission after a specified period."
"In the case where the device is destroyed, it remains the last position of the person concerned."
'The most expensive devices also have a flashlight that immediately signals the position of the person who slipped and is in a position that is extended without moving,' says Cech.
According to him, smartphones that are so intelligent that they are equipped with a navigation system can offer a comparable service after they have formatted it with a special prological.
The problem with the current tracking systems is that it is a device similar to that which is carried depending on the size of a lamp box or the smallest telephone devices.
We can always lose them.
According to Macro Weil's Pilina, that's why tests are being carried out to make devices that look like common digital watches.
"This will have the advantage that the potential attacker will not be able to recognize the tracking device."
"Or he'll realize after a while, which will give the police a little more time," he adds.
Whether the tracking device is developed as a bracelet or pendant, it will always use the same technology as to track cars.
This is a combination of the acquisition systems of a position using the GPS (which is commonly used in self-navigation) and a function of a mobile phone that alerts the current position of a vehicle.
