Support for democracy in Latin America continues to increase, as well as for private enterprises.
Crime has become a greater concern than unemployment.
And Brazil is seen as more influential than the United States in much of the region.
These are some of the conclusions of the last Latinobarometer survey taken in 18 countries and published exclusively by The Economist.
Since the survey has been carried out regularly since 1995, it follows the change of attitude in the region.
Two related elements are the results of this year's survey, conducted in September and early October.
The first is the rather sunny mood of Latin America.
The second is the increasing stability of attitudes towards democracy and its main institutions.
Support for democracy has increased significantly in several countries around the Pacific of South America (see table 1).
For example, in Peru, where economic growth has reached an average of 6 per cent per year since 2002, support for democracy has grown from at least 40 per cent in 2005 to 61 per cent this year.
It has also increased in Mexico, where the economy has recovered after a strong fall in production last year.
But only about half of the respondents in Mexico and Brazil, the two most populous countries in the region, are convinced democrats, reducing the regional average (see Table 2).
Some 44 per cent of the region's respondents expressed satisfaction with the way their country's democracy worked in practice; this was the same figure as last year, but with a strong increase of 25 per cent in 2001 (Figure 3)
