A Global Plan to Renovate Light
In Cancún yesterday, the United Nations proposed a plan for the renovation of domestic, commercial and industrial lighting in 100 countries to achieve a greenhouse gas reduction (GHG) corresponding to almost a third of the additional reduction required to stabilise the global climate by 2020.
This ambitious plan is in the wake of the great concrete projects that the United Nations hopes to adopt in Cancún to compensate for the absence of binding reduction commitments by industrialized countries.
According to yesterday's plan, if incandescent ampoules still monopolizing from 50% to 70% of the market were replaced by fluo-compact ampoules or, better, by electroluminescent diode ampoules (DEL or "LED" in English), the essence of the 1.8 billion tonnes of GHG (Gt) emitted on the planet to shed light on humans would be avoided.
The lighting is responsible for 8% of global emissions.
This is the equivalent of 70% of the emissions from the planetary car park.
In Copenhagen, last year, major issuing countries, such as the United States, China, Europe and others, including Canada, committed themselves to voluntary reduction plans that should lead to global GHG emissions from 53 Gt to 49 Gt.
But it will have to be subtracted from this 5 Gt balance sheet to stabilize by 2020 the rise in climate to 2 degrees centigrades in order to avoid becoming out of control.
In the incandescent ampoules, 95% of the energy is dissipated in the form of heat and the rest, or 5%, is produced by light.
With fluorinated ampoules, energy expenditure is reduced by 75% and with new ampoules in DEL, this need for energy is reduced twice again.
Fluo-Compact ampoules are averaged 6000 to 10,000 hours.
The new DEL ampoules, like those launched by the Philips manufacturer this week - this company also participated in the United Nations study - have a life expectancy of 25,000 hours and consume 80% less energy than an incandescent ampoule, which gives an idea of the economy possible with a replacement plan that would apply to 100 countries.
All these new ampoules can also work with reostats in addition to producing very little heat.
And they don't contain any mercury.
Several experts have posted reserves for fluorinated ampoules because they contain mercury and need to be disposed of as hazardous waste, which is not always possible in developing countries unless the manufacturers put in place signs.
But, says the report, the main source of mercury emissions on the planet is not the fluocompact ampoule, but the coal thermal plants, which emit a lot of mercury to produce spent electricity in incandescent ampoules.
In the United States alone, these plants emit 25,000 tonnes of mercury per year.
The report details the gains each country would make through this international programme.
For example, Indonesia would thus save one billion dollars a year in electricity purchases and eight million tons of CO2 or the equivalent of 3.5 thermal power plants whose construction would cost 2.5 billion.
